Manual on hatchery production of seabass and gilthead seabream /
Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations,

Volume 1: The first part covers the historical background and a discussion of the main factors that affect fish seed production. The second section describes the life history and biology of the species. This includes also a short section on microalgae, rotifers and brine shrimp. The third section of the first volume deals with hatchery production procedures, from broodstock management to production of live feed, egg management, larval rearing weaning, fry transport, and diseases.

Volume 2: Deals with the design and production of theb hatchery, engineering aspects of water supply, hydraulic circuits, and equipment used in the hatcheries. It also includes guidance on financial aspects that could be useful for project design, and operation of hatcheries.

director, Hank Broeckling ; producer, Bruce Macdonald ; KCPQ-TV.

Aquaculture began some 4,000 years ago in China, yet in the United States its history is relatively recent. Increasing emphasis, however, is being placed on the production and harvesting of fish, shrimps, molluscs, seaweeds and other aquatic organisms in man-controlled environments. Focuses on developments in the Pacific--the research being done in aquaculture, the problems encountered, the industry already developed and the prospects for the future. The second part of the program includes a discussion of a panel of experts discussing what they consider the present state of aquaculture and what they foresee as some of the limitations and future potential.
